A Day in the Life of an Urban Park Ranger

By Adam Farence

Wearing a light green uniform with a Smokey Bear hat, one of Manhattan’s urban park rangers happily pointed out the tree in Inwood Hill Park that a pair of screech owls call home.  “They’ve got a nice little condo in there,” he said.

The owls occupy a tulip tree near the southern end of the park. It was about noon when the ranger, Nick Baisley, 27, set up a tripod there, with a lens mounted on it and began an outdoor class that anyone walking past could join. It was noon.

Hoping to share the park’s hidden treasures, Baisley spoke with passersby, eagerly showing them where the owls live.

“A lot of people don’t talk to strangers in the park,” he acknowledged. But it’s part of his job to engage the public.

The weather cooperated: clear skies, little wind, spring warmth. Some plants and trees were already budding.

“We’ve known we’ve had a pair of screech owls here for a while now,” Baisley told several people who stopped. He explained how screech owls typically behave and how nearby blue jays can be “jerks.” When a blue jay sees an owl, it sometimes flies home and returns with other blue jays to harass it.

Baisley, 27, attached his phone to the camera lens, and at least a half dozen people took turns looking at a zoomed-in photo of a screech owl basking in the sun. Some had already heard about the owls’ home. Others marveled at the news.

The reason Baisley wanted to be an urban park ranger? He can be in nature and share the park’s beauty with people, especially during a pandemic when restrictions still prevent most social gatherings.

“I’ve always loved being outside,” he said. “We have a crazy opportunity to do good here in the city.”

As one of seven urban rangers working in Manhattan, his goal is to educate the public about the importance of parks. He also works to keep the parks enjoyable by dealing with anything potentially ruinous, like someone lighting fires or causing distress to animals. He also attends to anything that could detract from someone else’s experience, like blasting music.

The owl’s condo

“We might look like the fun police,” Baisley said. “But we want everyone to enjoy parks equally.”

He lost the single greatest opportunity to do good in the city — teaching school children about nature — for most of a year when the pandemic upended life.

School programs are the “bread and butter” of what the urban rangers do. In the interim, rangers did other kinds of volunteer work, like working at food distribution sites and, more recently, vaccination centers. School children, Baisley said, will return shortly.

But other residents still need his help. In Inwood Hill Park, a woman asked about setting up a nest for osprey. Baisley gave her the email address of a parks department colleague.

The rangers don’t only partner with schools; they seek out relationships with any organization interested in wildlife.  During the annual Christmas bird count, for instance, he and other rangers work with New York City Audubon, pandemic notwithstanding.

“It’s absolutely invaluable,” Kaitlyn Parkins, a conservation biologist for NYC Audubon, said of its relationship with the urban park rangers.

Hosted by the Central Park Conservancy, the rangers and NYC Audubon help direct and educate birders as they spot and count birds. They sometimes spot thousands.

NYC Audubon also relays animal rescue information to the rangers. “They’ve done a lot of rescues,” she said.

Earlier that morning near the park entrance, Baisley’s boss, Sgt. Robert Mastrianni, brought him up to speed on a duck in Central Park that needed saving. It sounded like a fishing line had torn up the feathers around its neck. Mastrianni and another ranger hopped in a NYC Parks van and left for Central Park, leaving Baisley to patrol Inwood Hill.

Rangering is not an office job, but the rangers do have offices. When Baisley arrived earlier this morning at the rangers’s Inwood Hill park office, a nondescript beige building that straddles the southern end of the park, he made coffee, changed into his uniform, turned on his radio, and looked to see if his colleagues had logged any complaints about misbehavior: littering, setting fires, blasting music.

But today, the duck maimed by fishing line was the big-ticket item. While Mastrianni and a few other rangers attempted a rescue, Baisley held his classroom and then patrolled the park. He chatted to visitors about natural rock formations like “palisades” – rock walls the Earth’s tectonic plates formed when the supercontinent Pangea broke apart.

He also explained how seemingly natural mounds near the owl’s condo were dirt covered mounds of crushed oyster shells left behind by the Lenape Native Americans.

Baisley always had an affinity for the outdoors, reflected in his higher education.

He attended Paul Smith’s College in the Adirondacks, studying forestry and working towards a bachelor’s degree in environmental science, a curriculum that included a class in maple syrup making. He finished his degree at Queens College and landed the ranger job in 2017. He makes about $51,000 a year and lives on Manhattan’s Upper West Side with his girlfriend and another friend.

Near the end of the workday, Baisley touched base with his boss to summarize what he had done. The search for the maimed duck had been unsuccessful, Mastrianni reported.

Baisley had stopped at a rocky outcrop overlooking the Hudson, a view unobstructed except for a stubborn peach tree growing up through a crack in the rock. A boat puttered up the river and the dull roar of traffic wafted up from below. Baisley pointed out the palisade rock formation on the Jersey side.

Restrictions have loosened since the start of the pandemic. Rangers can now give guided, socially distanced park tours for up to 30 masked people. Baseball and basketball games have returned. Baisley is feeling hopeful. His last task for the day, he said, was to create lesson plans for children when they came back to the parks to learn about nature.

“A lot of people have always known being outside is good for you,” he said.
